BSE update (14) Apr 2001 20010404.0678
[1
Date: 8 Apr 2001 13:03:28 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Xinhua News Agency [edited

BRUSSELS: A new case of mad cow disease has been found in Belgium, bringing
the number of mad cow cases in the country to 27, local television reported
on Friday. Television network RTBF said the new case was found in Flanders
in Antwerp Province, yet it did not say whether the case had been found by
screening tests or routine checks conducted by livestock farmers.
Beginning in January 2001, the European Union (EU) has instructed all its
member states to conduct screening tests on cattle more than 30 months of
age before the meat can enter the food chain. The 15-nation bloc also
instructed member states to ban for 6 months the use of animal feed made of
cattle meat and bonemeal and to bar the meat adjacent to the cattle backbone.
All these measures are resorted to in order to stamp out the brain-wasting
disease, a variant form of which affects human beings. The latest mad cow
disease scares in France and Germany have caused European beef sales to
decline by as much as a third despite the measures the EU has taken to
restore consumer confidence.
